linked into the Florida state insurance operations. Public history of UVE seems
to be five years with info. available for ten. So they've gone through some
weather/insurance cycles, and I guess they understand risks. On the one hand,
it seems that with book value going up almost ten fold in ten years, they are
doing something very right. Otoh, how the heck can they pay shareholders an
annual dividend of .40 from a $2.93 stated book value, and not be doing
something risky? (I might have a bit more confidence if, assuming there is such
risk, that I knew where that risk was, so that I could make some sort of
assessment. Too much assets in equities vs. fixed income in the reserves? Too
under-reserved? Too many under-priced policies? Something somewhere??)

This one's too tough for me, so I pass. Jmo, wrong though I seem to have been.
