Date:8/13/2010 5:52:34 PM
From:Spekulatius
re JNJ - yes I agree returns should be better going forward. What has happened
is that during the last 10 years, revenues and earnings have doubled, and the
PE has contracted by 1/2 (from ~20 to a PE of 11 now). In effect that has
caused the stock price to stagnate.

Of course that could happen again in 2020, JNJ revenues could double again and
the PE could compress from PE=11 to a PE=6.5. Don't laugh this is not
impossible. For example LLY (another ex- growth stock) briefly traded at a PE
of around 5-6 and for a good reason - it is currently shrinking and it's future
does not look that bright due to patent expiration.

I think a PE of 5 is unlikely with JNJ because they have multiple business
lines and a pretty good LT track record to adjust to changing conditions. On
the other hand, their growth going forward may be less than during the recent
decade because their pharma sector may not grow much at all and the rest cannot
pull the company enough forward to make up for lost momentum. However even if
JNJ were to trade at a PE of 9 in 10 years, i think the returns for JNJ will be
better.

The question is are they going to be good enough? I am shooting for double
digit total returns and I am not sure i will get this with JNJ. That's why i
don't own the stock right now.
